	    evaluating the while loop predicate.

Following up on footnotes and, this exercise addresses the question what should be the result of evaluating a JavaScript program that consists of a sequence containing declarations, blocks, expression statements, conditional statements and assignments outside of any function body. For this, JavaScript staticallyHere statically means that we can make the distinction by inspecting the program rather than by running it. distinguishes between value-producing and non-value-producing statements. All declarations are non-value-producing, and all expression statements, conditional statements and assignments are value-producing. A block is value-producing if its body statement is value-producing, and then its value is the value of its body statement. A sequence is value-producing if any of its component statements is value-producing, and then its value is the value of its last value-producing component statement. The value of an expression statement is the value of the expression. The value of a conditional statement is the value of the branch that gets executed, or the value undefined if that branch is not value-producing. The value of an assignment is the value of the expression to the right of its = sign. Finally, if the whole program is not value-producing, its value is the value undefined.
According to this specification, what are the values of the following programs?
1; 2; 3;
1; { if (true) { } else { 2; } }
1; const x = 2;
1; { let x = 2; { x = x + 3; } }
Modify the evaluate function of the previous section to adhere to this specification.
